    <a title="X" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/599861-x"><img alt="X" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1194239885p2/599861.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/10088199?book_show_action=true">Dec 07, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="X" class="user" itemprop="url" name="X" href="/user/show/599861-x">X</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780374516901" href="/book/show/19894.Basin_and_Range">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">geologists or people interested in geology</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer10088199" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13580099596267830708"> This was surprisingly good. It&apos;s not something I would have read if I hadn&apos;t needed to for school, but it was very interesting, and I may consider reading the rest of the series. The book covered mountain building, volcanism, mining, plate tectonics, and continental drift, and also gave brief historical accounts of famous geologists, while describing the author&apos;s field trip with a geology professor. At times it seemed to skip around too much, though it always came back to the main point of cont</span>
  <span id="freeText13580099596267830708" style="display:none"> This was surprisingly good. It's not something I would have read if I hadn't needed to for school, but it was very interesting, and I may consider reading the rest of the series. The book covered mountain building, volcanism, mining, plate tectonics, and continental drift, and also gave brief historical accounts of famous geologists, while describing the author's field trip with a geology professor. At times it seemed to skip around too much, though it always came back to the main point of continental drift, and on the positive side, the sometimes abrupt subject changes kept me alert while reading this book in 2 days. It was not at all dry or boring, though some of the technical terms would be lost on those who have not studied a little bit of geology. </span>
  <a data-text-id="13580099596267830708" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


