    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1222149617" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1222149617" />
    <a title="Claudia Putnam" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4162791-claudia-putnam"><img alt="Claudia Putnam" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1443509418p2/4162791.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1222149617?book_show_action=true">Aug 20, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Claudia Putnam" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Claudia Putnam" href="/user/show/4162791-claudia-putnam">Claudia Putnam</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780374516901" href="/book/show/19894.Basin_and_Range">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4162791-claudia-putnam?shelf=journalistic-synthetic-non-fiction">journalistic-synthetic-non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4162791-claudia-putnam?shelf=science">science</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1222149617" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1704596667762399068">Whew. I stopped reading this for a while, and when I restarted, I had to go back to the beginning, because I hadn&apos;t retained enough, even though maybe only a year, or less, had passed. <br/><br/>A glossary would have helped. Also maps, diagrams, and photos or at least illustrations. While someone else I know, a poet, who happened to be reading this book at the same time, reminded me of McPhee&apos;s statement that geology is one of the more poetic/metaphoric &quot;languages,&quot; of the sciences--country rock, outwash </span>
  <span id="freeText1704596667762399068" style="display:none">Whew. I stopped reading this for a while, and when I restarted, I had to go back to the beginning, because I hadn't retained enough, even though maybe only a year, or less, had passed. <br /><br />A glossary would have helped. Also maps, diagrams, and photos or at least illustrations. While someone else I know, a poet, who happened to be reading this book at the same time, reminded me of McPhee's statement that geology is one of the more poetic/metaphoric "languages," of the sciences--country rock, outwash plains, drowned rivers, orogeny, surface of no strain, angle of repose--McPhee also discusses how jargonistic it is. Eventually, as he says, "verbal deposits" thickened. "Someone developed enough effrontery to call a piece of our earth an epieugeosyncline. There were those who said interfluve when they meant between two streams, and perfectly good word like mesopotamian would do."<br /><br />"A cactolith, according the American Geological Institutes Glossary of Geology and Related Sciences, was a 'quasi-horizontal chnolith composed of anastomosing ductoliths, whose distal ends curl like a harpolith, thicken like a sphenolith, or bulge discordantly like an akmolith or ethmolith." <br /><br />So, okay, you see the problem of doing a deep-dive and then rendering this subject matter for the lay reader. Which is something McPhee is known for and normally excels at.<br /><br />However, as the science became more differentiated, it also started making better distinctions—not much Andesite in the Andes, very little granite is actually granite, though most geologists go on calling it that in their everyday vernacular. <br /><br />That is to say, you learn a lot in this book. What McPhee does particularly well is bring through a sort of astounded reverence and a sense of the deep silence you feel, especially in a place like Nevada, encountering the massive timescales. You really do come up against these in some places in the land, especially in the West. I remember reading Stegner, where he describes going east to college and how the land became progressively greener. You no longer could see or feel the earth, he said, mournfully. To my Eastern-born eyes, the West was alien, dry, boring, at first. I had to learn to see, but now the East is as horrifyingly bland as Stegner felt it to be. Covered, as Peter Brannen quoted a paleontologist saying in The Ends of the World, in “photosynthetic glop.” You can’t see anything.<br /><br />Considering I dog-eared about every fourth page, you’d think I’d give this book 5 stars but I can’t, quite, because:<br /><br />--I wanted to hear more about the female geologist he mentioned in the early part of the book—not because she’s female but because he made her sound so interesting and also led me to believe she’d be turning up later<br /><br />--The book seemed to thin out later on, probably because it’s a series of magazine articles, and to become a little less about geology<br /><br />--I didn’t understand how his friend was able to claim those tailing piles and I wanted to. I mean, a lot of time was spent on that endeavor, so I thought he might as well have explained how you go about striking a claim in these times. <br /><br />I didn’t mind that he never tried to explain the UFO, because it was part of the holy mystery of the wide open spaces and missing time (the millions and I guess sometimes billions of years that disappear from the geological record in Nevada—all around me in Colorado 150 million years are missing). However, I looked it up and there was a test rocket launch at that moment in that area. Here’s a link… this guy is a little nuts but his explanation sounds about right. <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://cpacker.org/misc/mcphee.html">http://cpacker.org/misc/mcphee.html</a><br /><br />Anyway, awesome read, highly recommended. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1704596667762399068" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


