<div id="review_974113801" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/974113801" />
    <a title="Dave" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/757896-dave"><img alt="Dave" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1436728029p2/757896.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/974113801?book_show_action=true">Jun 21, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dave" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dave" href="/user/show/757896-dave">Dave</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer974113801" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9662032881384237589"><pre><br/>There was much to love about this book, but also<br/>a few things that for me were mildly off-putting.<br/><br/>First, some things that resonated for me:<br/><br/> • McPhee&apos;s passion for Nature &amp; decoding<br/> some of its mysteries is, hopefully, contagious<br/> <br/> • Floating on the Great Salt Lake - water <br/> so saline that only his shoulders, buttocks <br/> and heels seemed to be wet. As if he were a <br/> huge Water Strider, supported only by surface<br/> tension<br/> <br/> • Bishop Ussher and his &quot;calculation&quot; for <br/> the age of the Earth - being off by a fa</pre></span>
  <span id="freeText9662032881384237589" style="display:none"><pre><br />There was much to love about this book, but also<br />a few things that for me were mildly off-putting.<br /><br />First, some things that resonated for me:<br /><br /> • McPhee's passion for Nature &amp; decoding<br /> some of its mysteries is, hopefully, contagious<br /> <br /> • Floating on the Great Salt Lake - water <br /> so saline that only his shoulders, buttocks <br /> and heels seemed to be wet. As if he were a <br /> huge Water Strider, supported only by surface<br /> tension<br /> <br /> • Bishop Ussher and his "calculation" for <br /> the age of the Earth - being off by a factor<br /> of more than 700,000 gives new hope to all <br /> innumerate people for success in life in<br /> spite of that failing ;-)<br /> <br /> • The story of James Hutton and the first<br /> appreciation of "deep time" - A biography of<br /> that remarkable man has to be well worth <br /> reading<br /> <br /> • A grounding discussion of the vastness of<br /> time this planet has been in existence and how<br /> very tiny a portion and role we've played in <br /> that drama<br /> <br /> • The sobering discussion of the two great <br /> extinctions may add a bit of force to the <br /> advice to <i>carpe deum</i><br /> <br /> • The gradual acceptance of plate tectonics<br /> as a formative force of nature and all that <br /> implies about the changing face of the Earth<br /> <br />All that and more make this book a must read, a <br />small expenditure of time that will be well <br />rewarded. Yet, there are a couple of minor <br />quibbles that held me back to only 4 stars:<br /><br /> • Why all the technical geological jargon<br /> sans footnotes or glossary to supply needed<br /> meaning? A glaring example is page 28 where <br /> we see no less than 28 terms (rock types I <br /> suppose, but what types?) These were words <br /> that I could neither spell nor pronounce so<br /> they truly added nothing - so, to what purpose?<br /> <br /> • Some fairly complicated descriptions of<br /> the tortured processes that occur in creating<br /> the surface effects we live among, but not all<br /> of us are able to readily visualize such<br /> things - would a few photos or line drawings<br /> have been too much to expect? <br /></pre><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9662032881384237589" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


